Looking at this again, I notice a few things:

1. The welcome banner shows correctly in the screenshot - it's aligned to the left
2. The /help output is all messed up

The key difference: The welcome is written using `writeln()` which adds `\r\n`. But the command output is written using `write()` with just `\n` characters.

In terminal emulation, `\n` (Line Feed) only moves the cursor down one line - it does NOT return to column 0. You need `\r` (Carriage Return) to go back to column 0.

So when the help text has `\n`, the cursor goes down but stays at whatever column it was at. This explains the staggered output!

The fix is simple: In the shellService output, I need to use `\r\n` instead of just `\n`.

Let me look at the runCommand function and how output is being processed.

Actually, looking at the code:
```javascript
case 'builtin': {
  const result = await shellExecutor.executeBuiltin(command, context);
  if (result) {
    onOutput(result + '\n');
  }
  return 0;
}
```

And the help output has embedded `\n` characters in the template literal. When these are written to xterm, they don't include `\r`, so the cursor doesn't return to column 0.

The fix: Replace `\n` with `\r\n` in the output before writing to terminal, OR configure xterm to handle `\n` as `\r\n`.

xterm.js has an option called `convertEol` which, when true, converts `\n` to `\r\n`. Let me add that option!

